  "prompt": "How do i (a Java developer) get an Adobe Experience Manager (AEM) instance for learning the CMS? I'm not Adobe Parner.",
  "response": "As a Java developer looking to learn Adobe Experience Manager (AEM), here are several ways to get an AEM instance:\n\n1. Free Trial from Adobe\n- Go to Adobe's official website\n- Sign up for a 30-day free trial of AEM Sites\n- Requires creating an Adobe account\n\n2. Local Development Setup\n- Download AEM Quickstart JAR from Adobe's website\n- Requires an Adobe login/account\n- Provides a full local development environment\n\n3. Docker Images\n- Official Adobe AEM docker images (requires Adobe login)\n- Docker Hub has some community AEM-like images\n- For example: https://hub.docker.com/r/paulobezerra/aem63\n\n4. Open-Source Alternative\n- Apache Sling (foundation technology for AEM)\n- Similar concepts, good for learning fundamentals\n\n5. Community Resources\n- WKND Tutorial from Adobe includes downloadable AEM instance\n- https://github.com/adobe/aem-guides-wknd\n\n6. Academic/Student Options\n- Some universities have licensing agreements\n- Check with your institution\n\nRecommended Path:\n1. Official Adobe Free Trial\n2. Follow WKND Tutorial\n3. Practice local development\n\nPro Tips:\n- Ensure you have Java 8/11 installed\n- Minimum 8GB RAM recommended\n- Have at least 20GB free disk space",
